[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] In computing, **data transformation** is the process of converting data from one format or structure into another format or structure.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] It is a fundamental aspect of most data integration and data management tasks such as data wrangling, data warehousing, data integration and application integration.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Data transformation can be simple or complex based on the required changes to the data between the source (initial) data and the target (final) data.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Data transformation is typically performed via a mixture of manual and automated steps.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Tools and technologies used for data transformation can vary widely based on the format, structure, complexity, and volume of the data being transformed.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] A master data recast is another form of data transformation where the entire database of data values is transformed or recast without extracting the data from the database.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] All data in a well-designed database is directly or indirectly related to a limited set of master database tables by a network of foreign key constraints.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Each foreign key constraint is dependent upon a unique database index from the parent database table.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Therefore, when the proper master database table is recast with a different unique index, the directly and indirectly related data are also recast or restated.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] The directly and indirectly related data may also still be viewed in the original form since the original unique index still exists with the master data.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Also, the database recast must be done in such a way as to not impact the applications architecture software.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] When the data mapping is indirect via a mediating data model, the process is also called **data mediation**.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Data transformation can be divided into the following steps, each applicable as needed based on the complexity of the transformation required.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] These steps are often the focus of developers or technical data analysts who may use multiple specialized tools to perform their tasks.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Traditionally, data transformation has been a bulk or batch process, whereby developers write code or implement transformation rules in a data integration tool, and then execute that code or those rules on large volumes of data.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This process can follow the linear set of steps as described in the data transformation process above.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Batch data transformation is the cornerstone of virtually all data integration technologies such as data warehousing, data migration and application integration.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] When data must be transformed and delivered with low latency, the term "microbatch" is often used.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This refers to small batches of data (e.g. a small number of rows or a small set of data objects) that can be processed very quickly and delivered to the target system when needed.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Traditional data transformation processes have served companies well for decades.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] The various tools and technologies (data profiling, data visualization, data cleansing, data integration etc.) have matured and most (if not all) enterprises transform enormous volumes of data that feed internal and external applications, data warehouses and other data stores.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This traditional process also has limitations that hamper its overall efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] The people who need to use the data (e.g. business users) do not play a direct role in the data transformation process.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Typically, users hand over the data transformation task to developers who have the necessary coding or technical skills to define the transformations and execute them on the data.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This process leaves the bulk of the work of defining the required transformations to the developer, which often in turn do not have the same domain knowledge as the business user.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] The developer interprets the business user requirements and implements the related code/logic.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This has the potential of introducing errors into the process (through misinterpreted requirements), and also increases the time to arrive at a solution.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This problem has given rise to the need for agility and self-service in data integration (i.e. empowering the user of the data and enabling them to transform the data themselves interactively).
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] There are companies that provide self-service data transformation tools.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] They are aiming to efficiently analyze, map and transform large volumes of data without the technical knowledge and process complexity that currently exists.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] While these companies use traditional batch transformation, their tools enable more interactivity for users through visual platforms and easily repeated scripts.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Still, there might be some compatibility issues (e.g. new data sources like IoT may not work correctly with older tools) and compliance limitations due to the difference in data governance, preparation and audit practices.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Although interactive data transformation follows the same data integration process steps as batch data integration, the key difference is that the steps are not necessarily followed in a linear fashion and typically don't require significant technical skills for completion.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] There are a number of companies that provide interactive data transformation tools, including Trifacta, Alteryx and Paxata.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] They are aiming to efficiently analyze, map and transform large volumes of data while at the same time abstracting away some of the technical complexity and processes which take place under the hood.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Interactive data transformation solutions provide an integrated visual interface that combines the previously disparate steps of data analysis, data mapping and code generation/execution and data inspection.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] That is, if changes are made at one step (like for example renaming), the software automatically updates the preceding or following steps accordingly.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Interfaces for interactive data transformation incorporate visualizations to show the user patterns and anomalies in the data so they can identify erroneous or outlying values.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Once they've finished transforming the data, the system can generate executable code/logic, which can be executed or applied to subsequent similar data sets.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] There are numerous languages available for performing data transformation.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Many transformation languages require a grammar to be provided.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] In many cases, the grammar is structured using something closely resembling Backus–Naur form (BNF).
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] There are numerous languages available for such purposes varying in their accessibility (cost) and general usefulness.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Additionally, companies such as Trifacta and Paxata have developed domain-specific transformational languages (DSL) for servicing and transforming datasets.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] The development of domain-specific languages has been linked to increased productivity and accessibility for non-technical users.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Trifacta's “Wrangle” is an example of such a domain-specific language.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Another advantage of the recent domain-specific transformational languages trend is that a domain-specific transformational language can abstract the underlying execution of the logic defined in the domain-specific transformational language.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] They can also utilize that same logic in various processing engines, such as Spark, MapReduce, and Dataflow.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] In other words, with a domain-specific transformational language, the transformation language is not tied to the underlying engine.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] Although transformational languages are typically best suited for transformation, something as simple as regular expressions can be used to achieve useful transformation.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] A text editor like vim, emacs or TextPad supports the use of regular expressions with arguments.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] This would allow all instances of a particular pattern to be replaced with another pattern using parts of the original pattern.
[src:serde-rust/data-transformation] In other words, all instances of a function invocation of foo with three arguments, followed by a function invocation with two arguments would be replaced with a single function invocation using some or all of the original set of arguments.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:serde-rust/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:serde-rust/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:serde-rust/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:serde-rust/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:serde-rust/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:serde-rust/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:serde-rust/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:serde-rust/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:serde-rust/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:serde-rust/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:serde-rust/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:serde-rust/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:serde-rust/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:serde-rust/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:serde-rust/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:serde-rust/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:serde-rust/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:serde-rust/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:serde-rust/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:serde-rust/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:serde-rust/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:serde-rust/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:serde-rust/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:serde-rust/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:serde-rust/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:serde-rust/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:serde-rust/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:serde-rust/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:serde-rust/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:serde-rust/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:serde-rust/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:serde-rust/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:serde-rust/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:serde-rust/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:serde-rust/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:serde-rust/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:serde-rust/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:serde-rust/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:serde-rust/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:serde-rust/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:serde-rust/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:serde-rust/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:serde-rust/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:serde-rust/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:serde-rust/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:serde-rust/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:serde-rust/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:serde-rust/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:serde-rust/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:serde-rust/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:serde-rust/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:serde-rust/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:serde-rust/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:serde-rust/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:serde-rust/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:serde-rust/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:serde-rust/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:serde-rust/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:serde-rust/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:serde-rust/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:serde-rust/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:serde-rust/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:serde-rust/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:serde-rust/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:serde-rust/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:serde-rust/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:serde-rust/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:serde-rust/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:serde-rust/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:serde-rust/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:serde-rust/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:serde-rust/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:serde-rust/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:serde-rust/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:serde-rust/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:serde-rust/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:serde-rust/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:serde-rust/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:serde-rust/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:serde-rust/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:serde-rust/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:serde-rust/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:serde-rust/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:serde-rust/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:serde-rust/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:serde-rust/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:serde-rust/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] Serde is a framework for ***ser***ializing and ***de***serializing Rust data structures efficiently and generically.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] The Serde ecosystem consists of data structures that know how to serialize and deserialize themselves along with data formats that know how to serialize and deserialize other things.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] Serde provides the layer by which these two groups interact with each other, allowing any supported data structure to be serialized and deserialized using any supported data format.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] See the Serde website https://serde.rs for additional documentation and usage examples.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] Where many other languages rely on runtime reflection for serializing data, Serde is instead built on Rust’s powerful trait system.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] A data structure that knows how to serialize and deserialize itself is one that implements Serde’s `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits (or uses Serde’s derive attribute to automatically generate implementations at compile time).
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] This avoids any overhead of reflection or runtime type information.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] In fact in many situations the interaction between data structure and data format can be completely optimized away by the Rust compiler, leaving Serde serialization to perform the same speed as a handwritten serializer for the specific selection of data structure and data format.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] The following is a partial list of data formats that have been implemented for Serde by the community.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] Generic data structure deserialization framework.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] Generic data structure serialization framework.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] that can be deserialized from any data format supported by Serde.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] that can deserialize any data structure supported by Serde.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] that can be serialized into any data format supported by Serde.
[src:serde-rust/latest-serde] that can serialize any data structure supported by Serde.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:serde-rust/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In computer science, **reflective programming** or **reflection** is the ability of a process to examine, introspect, and modify its own structure and behavior.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] The earliest computers were programmed in their native assembly languages, which were inherently reflective, as these original architectures could be programmed by defining instructions as data and using self-modifying code.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] As the bulk of programming moved to higher-level compiled languages such as ALGOL, COBOL, Fortran, Pascal, and C, this reflective ability largely disappeared until new programming languages with reflection built into their type systems appeared.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Brian Cantwell Smith's 1982 doctoral dissertation introduced the notion of computational reflection in procedural programming languages and the notion of the meta-circular interpreter as a component of 3-Lisp.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection helps programmers make generic software libraries to display data, process different formats of data, perform serialization and deserialization of data for communication, or do bundling and unbundling of data for containers or bursts of communication.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflective systems may provide a mirror type, used as a decoupled reflection of an object or identifier.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Effective use of reflection almost always requires a plan: A design framework, encoding description, object library, a map of a database or entity relations.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection makes a language more suited to network-oriented code.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] For example, it assists languages such as Java to operate well in networks by enabling libraries for serialization, bundling and varying data formats.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Languages without reflection such as C are required to use auxiliary compilers for tasks like Abstract Syntax Notation to produce code for serialization and bundling.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be used for observing and modifying program execution at runtime.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] A reflection-oriented program component can monitor the execution of an enclosure of code and can modify itself according to a desired goal of that enclosure.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] This is typically accomplished by dynamically assigning program code at runtime.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In object-oriented programming languages such as Java, reflection allows *inspection* of classes, interfaces, fields and methods at runtime without knowing the names of the interfaces, fields, methods at compile time.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] It also allows *instantiation* of new objects and *invocation* of methods.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is often used as part of software testing, such as for the runtime creation/instantiation of mock objects.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is also a key strategy for metaprogramming.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In some object-oriented programming languages such as C# and Java, reflection can be used to bypass member accessibility rules.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] For C#-properties this can be achieved by writing directly onto the (usually invisible) backing field of a non-public property.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] It is also possible to find non-public methods of classes and types and manually invoke them.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] This works for project-internal files as well as external libraries such as .NET's assemblies and Java's archives.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] A language that supports reflection provides a number of features available at runtime that would otherwise be difficult to accomplish in a lower-level language.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] These features can be implemented in different ways.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In MOO, reflection forms a natural part of everyday programming idiom.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] When verbs (methods) are called, various variables such as `verb` (the name of the verb being called) and `this` (the object on which the verb is called) are populated to give the context of the call.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Compiled languages rely on their runtime system to provide information about the source code.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] A compiled Objective-C executable, for example, records the names of all methods in a block of the executable, providing a table to correspond these with the underlying methods (or selectors for these methods) compiled into the program.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In a compiled language that supports runtime creation of functions, such as Common Lisp, the runtime environment must include a compiler or an interpreter.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be implemented for languages without built-in reflection by using a program transformation system to define automated source-code changes.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection may allow a user to create unexpected control flow paths through an application, potentially bypassing security measures.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Historical vulnerabilities in Java caused by unsafe reflection allowed code retrieved from potentially untrusted remote machines to break out of the Java sandbox security mechanism.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] A large scale study of 120 Java vulnerabilities in 2013 concluded that unsafe reflection is the most common vulnerability in Java, though not the most exploited.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Runtime reflection systems introduce a non-negligible runtime performance overhead.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] For instance, in Java, because reflective operations are resolved dynamically at execution time, many compiler and JVM optimizations—such as method inlining, static binding, and aggressive just-in-time specialization—cannot be fully applied.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] As a consequence, reflective calls are typically slower than their statically resolved counterparts.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In sequential applications, reflection can significantly increase execution time and memory consumption when used in performance-critical code paths.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In multithreaded applications, reflective implementations generally preserve scalability, but still exhibit noticeably higher absolute execution times—commonly between 1.5x and 10× slower—than equivalent non-reflective code.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] In languages like C++ and Rust, reflection is performed at compile time.
[src:serde-rust/reflection-computer-programming] Compile-time reflection systems are weaker than runtime reflection systems like those of Java and C#, but incur no runtime overhead due to being performed during compilation.
