[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
