[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:serde-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
